HEADWORD: Giallolino
<hw>Gial`lo*li"no</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[It., from
<ets>giallo</ets> yellow, prob. fr. OHG. <ets>gelo</ets>, G.
<ets>gelb</ets>; akin to E. <ets>yellow</ets>.]</ety> <def>A term
variously employed by early writers on art, though commonly designating
the yellow oxide of lead, or massicot.</def>
<rj><au>Fairholt.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

